          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ca-001T/" title="Compact subset of a metric space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001T/" display-uri="ca-001T" type="local">compact</fr:link> <fr:link href="/ca-000K/" title="Metric Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000K/" display-uri="ca-000K" type="local">Metric Space</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ca-001L/" title="Continuous function between metric spaces" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001L/" display-uri="ca-001L" type="local">continuous function</fr:link>, then there are points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f(a)\leq  f(x)\leq  f(b).]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>We see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(X)]]></fr:tex> is compact because the <fr:link href="/ca-001X/" title="Continuous image of a compact subset is compact" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001X/" display-uri="ca-001X" type="local">Continuous image of a compact subset is compact</fr:link>, and therefore <fr:link href="/ca-000P/" title="Closed Subset" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000P/" display-uri="ca-000P" type="local">closed</fr:link> and <fr:link href="/ca-001U/" title="" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001U/" display-uri="ca-001U" type="local">bounded</fr:link> since <fr:link href="/ca-001V/" title="Compact subsets of metric spaces are closed and bounded" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001V/" display-uri="ca-001V" type="local">Compact subsets of metric spaces are closed and bounded</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha :=\inf  f(X)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta :=\sup  f(X)]]></fr:tex>. By <fr:link href="/ca-0007/" title="Least-Upper-Bound Property" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0007/" display-uri="ca-0007" type="local">Least-Upper-Bound Property</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(X)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ca-000P/" title="Closed Subset" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000P/" display-uri="ca-000P" type="local">closed</fr:link>, we see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ,\beta \in  f(X)]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
