            <fr:title text="Subsets of a LUB-set which are bounded below have a supremum">Subsets of a LUB-set which are bounded below have a supremum</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link href="/ca-0003/" title="Ordered Set" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0003/" display-uri="ca-0003" type="local">Ordered Set</fr:link> with the <fr:link href="/ca-0007/" title="Least-Upper-Bound Property" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0007/" display-uri="ca-0007" type="local">Least-Upper-Bound Property</fr:link>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex> be non-empty and suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ca-0004/" title="Upper bound, bounded above" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0004/" display-uri="ca-0004" type="local">bounded below</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be the set of all lower bounds of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha =\sup (L)]]></fr:tex> exists in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha =\inf (B)]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
