            <fr:title text="Uniqueness of Real Field">Uniqueness of Real Field</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Suppose we have two ordered fields <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> which both have the <fr:link href="/ca-0007/" title="Least-Upper-Bound Property" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0007/" display-uri="ca-0007" type="local">Least-Upper-Bound Property</fr:link> and each contain the rational numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> as a subfield. Then there exists an order-preserving field isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  R_{1}\to  R_{2}]]></fr:tex>, i.e., <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>Since the ordered field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> with the LUB property and containing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is essentially unique, we refer to it as the <html:dfn>Real Numbers</html:dfn> and write it as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>19</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Just a sketch of the proof.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Step 1:</html:strong> the fields <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> are both character zero, i.e., there is no <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{R} + \cdots  + 1_{R}=0]]></fr:tex> (the sum of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{R}]]></fr:tex> vanishes). This is never true for either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Step 2:</html:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is order-dense in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{i}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Step 3:</html:strong> Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}\colon  \mathbb {Q}\cap  R_{1}\to  R_{2}]]></fr:tex> be a function taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> in the sense that if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  R_{1}\cap \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}(q)=q]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>We extend this <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{0}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  R_{1}\to  R_{2}]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(r)=\sup \{f(q)\mid  q<r\}]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  R_{1}]]></fr:tex>. Then by the order-density of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, this <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is an order isomorphism.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Step 4:</html:strong> The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> we just constructed is a field isomorphism.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
